WEBVTT

00:01.970 --> 00:04.951
Ugh. I am dreading this trip.

00:04.952 --> 00:06.253
Come on. You love Montreal.

00:06.254 --> 00:08.789
Not when the hosts
are stabbing me in the back.

00:08.790 --> 00:11.158
That was Jay with

00:11.159 --> 00:12.359
the advance team.

00:12.360 --> 00:13.760
Last week, this group

00:13.761 --> 00:16.897
of Canadian divers
discovered this wreckage

00:16.898 --> 00:21.268
of the HMS <i>Wanderer,</i>
disappeared in 1848

00:21.269 --> 00:23.303
while trying to reach the North Pole.

00:23.304 --> 00:25.155
With a name like that,
I'm not surprised.

00:25.156 --> 00:29.943
They're claiming it planted a flag
for Canada in the Northwest Passage.

00:29.944 --> 00:32.267
Because it sank there in 1848?

00:32.268 --> 00:35.382
Right? And meanwhile,

00:35.383 --> 00:39.453
Russia, Norway, Denmark
are all calling dibs.

00:39.454 --> 00:41.221
On the North Pole?

00:41.222 --> 00:43.023
Well, I guess Santa will be next.

00:43.024 --> 00:44.124
The fact is,

00:44.125 --> 00:47.461
the melting ice cap is,
among other things,

00:47.462 --> 00:50.230
a massive strategic opportunity.

00:50.231 --> 00:52.999
Shipping lanes, natural resources,

00:53.000 --> 00:54.234
fishing rights.

00:54.235 --> 00:57.938
What we achieve at this
summit could well determine

00:57.939 --> 01:01.041
the balance of power for
the next... hundred years.

01:01.042 --> 01:02.576
Assuming the world exists.

01:02.577 --> 01:05.412
Not a given, at the rate
the ice is melting up there.

01:05.413 --> 01:08.415
Thanks, Dr. Doom, but I
actually have to just focus

01:08.416 --> 01:10.784
on one monumental
global issue at a time.

01:10.785 --> 01:12.452
JASON: Has anyone seen my passport?

01:12.453 --> 01:15.689
The one I found in the dryer
after the India trip?

01:15.690 --> 01:17.824
- Possibly.
- Yeah, I have it.

01:17.825 --> 01:20.327
So, are you getting
psyched for Montreal?

01:20.328 --> 01:22.896
Ah, not as much as Piper.
She's all about Bella Rossi

01:22.897 --> 01:24.798
and the big scoop
for the school paper.

01:24.799 --> 01:26.399
How cool is it that Mom is letting you

01:26.400 --> 01:27.567
tag along with your girlfriend

01:27.568 --> 01:29.603
so she can interview
the woman who's gonna be

01:29.604 --> 01:32.139
outside the hotel protesting Mom

01:32.140 --> 01:33.340
and the summit?

01:33.341 --> 01:34.474
It's pretty cool, I guess.

01:34.475 --> 01:36.209
Gosh, I'm overwhelmed.

01:36.210 --> 01:37.878
HENRY: Well, listen, there are some

01:37.879 --> 01:39.079
beautiful churches up there

01:39.080 --> 01:40.514
you guys might want
to check out. You know,

01:40.515 --> 01:41.848
the Jesuits were
the first missionaries

01:41.849 --> 01:43.717
- to New France.
- First?!

01:43.718 --> 01:46.486
Wow! I should finish packing.

01:46.487 --> 01:48.722
Yeah, they were the radical
reformers of their day.

01:48.723 --> 01:50.223
You... ah.

01:50.224 --> 01:54.628
Oh, honey, I think that Jesuit
churches are pretty cool.

01:54.629 --> 01:56.163
Well, I don't know how

01:56.164 --> 01:58.165
the Canadians are gonna
be able to resist you, eh?

01:58.166 --> 02:00.199
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

02:01.868 --> 02:03.236
- Hey.
- Hey.

02:03.237 --> 02:05.105
Oh, the secretary said she wants
to stop by the Chip Harding

02:05.106 --> 02:06.606
- meeting on the way to Andrews.
- Hmm.

02:06.607 --> 02:07.833
But she said to get
started without her.

02:07.834 --> 02:08.775
Copy that.

02:08.776 --> 02:10.610
You ready for your part
of the Future Energy pitch?

02:10.610 --> 02:13.180
- Oh, of course.
- Hey. Hey, hey, hey, hey.

02:13.181 --> 02:14.548
You're the one that wanted
to get more involved in policy.

02:14.549 --> 02:16.249
And I'm very thankful to the secretary

02:16.250 --> 02:18.051
for allowing me to spread my wings

02:18.052 --> 02:19.953
under your expert
supervision, of course.

02:19.954 --> 02:21.788
It's just... it just burns me

02:21.789 --> 02:23.857
that we have to suck
up to an oil magnate.

02:23.858 --> 02:26.259
- Blake, Congress cut our...
- Cut our funding. I know.

02:26.260 --> 02:28.261
The last word on practically
every state initiative.

02:28.262 --> 02:30.530
And I get why the World
Expo is a critical showcase

02:30.531 --> 02:33.066
for American companies in a
ferocious global marketplace.

02:33.067 --> 02:34.467
It's just...

02:34.468 --> 02:36.770
It's just a tad ironic
that our big opportunity

02:36.771 --> 02:38.872
to promote American
renewable energy at the expo

02:38.873 --> 02:41.208
is being sponsored by Big Oil and Gas.

02:41.209 --> 02:43.543
Dude, this is not the irony hill
you want to die on.

02:43.544 --> 02:46.613
If Chip Harding doesn't pony up,
we'll be saying "Buy American"

02:46.614 --> 02:48.248
with dioramas and sock puppets.

02:48.249 --> 02:50.350
So let's get on board,
'cause this is our only shot

02:50.351 --> 02:51.725
to compete with China
at the expo, okay?

02:51.726 --> 02:52.817
Yeah.

02:52.818 --> 02:53.770
- Come on.
- Okay.

02:53.771 --> 02:54.754
- We got this.
- Okay.

02:54.755 --> 02:57.056
BLAKE: <i>And then the Hall
of Renewables is here.</i>

02:59.159 --> 03:00.994
I heard China has a holodeck,

03:00.995 --> 03:03.730
robot dancers, and free hoverboards.

03:03.731 --> 03:05.732
Well, we have food by Rachael Ray.

03:05.733 --> 03:07.701
And a pre-taped video
of Jennifer Lawrence

03:07.702 --> 03:09.402
personally lobbying world leaders

03:09.403 --> 03:11.671
on behalf of American
companies like yours.

03:11.672 --> 03:14.474
- Mm-hmm.
- But your pitch

03:14.475 --> 03:17.310
has a fundamental problem.

03:17.311 --> 03:18.240
The nuclear power section?

03:18.241 --> 03:19.713
It's taking up a lot
of real estate here,

03:19.714 --> 03:22.249
and you've neglected
good old natural gas.

03:22.250 --> 03:25.418
Well, nuclear power produces
carbon-free electricity,

03:25.419 --> 03:27.354
while natural gas does not.

03:27.355 --> 03:29.489
And most climate scientists
see nuclear

03:29.490 --> 03:31.258
as the key transition technology

03:31.259 --> 03:33.093
until renewables
become more efficient.

03:33.094 --> 03:36.196
The bridge to renewables
is not nuclear, my dear.

03:36.197 --> 03:37.330
It's gas.

03:37.331 --> 03:39.366
It's cheap, has half
the emissions of coal,

03:39.367 --> 03:41.268
and most importantly,
it won't melt down

03:41.269 --> 03:43.637
and make the neighborhood
children glow in the dark.

03:43.638 --> 03:45.739
Uh, due respect, Mr. Harding,

03:45.740 --> 03:48.275
no child or anyone has ever
glowed in the dark from any...

03:48.276 --> 03:50.110
- Ma'am.
- Mr. Harding.

03:50.111 --> 03:51.711
So good to see you again.

03:51.712 --> 03:54.281
I'm on my way to Montreal,
but I couldn't leave

03:54.282 --> 03:55.615
without stopping in to say hi.

03:55.616 --> 03:58.151
I'm happy to hear that
the Arctic is a top priority

03:58.152 --> 03:59.653
of the Dalton administration.

03:59.654 --> 04:00.887
It's a brave new world.

04:00.888 --> 04:02.589
Everybody wants a piece,
myself included.

04:02.590 --> 04:06.426
Well, I am eager to
negotiate a contract

04:06.427 --> 04:07.928
that will be fair to all of us.

04:07.929 --> 04:11.197
And I wanted to thank you again
for your generous pledge

04:11.198 --> 04:13.133
to our World Expo pavilion. Wow.

04:13.134 --> 04:14.301
- Yeah.
- Yeah. Yes.

04:14.302 --> 04:15.568
- Yes.
- Yeah.

04:15.569 --> 04:17.504
It is being held
in my home state of Texas.

04:17.505 --> 04:20.473
Wouldn't want to fumble the ball
on the home field, right?

04:20.474 --> 04:22.909
Not at all, which is why
I'm so concerned

04:22.910 --> 04:24.945
there's no section on natural gas.

04:24.946 --> 04:27.580
If we're talking future energy,
we need to tell folks

04:27.581 --> 04:30.216
that gas is cheap,
has half the emissions of coal,

04:30.217 --> 04:32.919
and most importantly,
folks won't glow in the dark.

04:32.920 --> 04:34.421
Let me tell you something else.

04:34.422 --> 04:36.489
So, wait, nuclear's gone,
just like that?

04:36.490 --> 04:39.526
Well, it's not gone, it's just,

04:39.527 --> 04:41.494
it's not a part of "future energy."

04:41.495 --> 04:43.563
Okay, well, can it be part of...?

04:43.564 --> 04:45.432
Kat, have you heard anything
from Jay at the summit?

04:45.433 --> 04:47.233
Deputy talks suggest that Canada
is still holding firm

04:47.234 --> 04:48.735
on the HMS <i>Wanderer.</i>

04:48.736 --> 04:51.137
Crap.

04:51.138 --> 04:53.840
Okay, I have spent weeks
with those briefing books.

04:53.841 --> 04:55.575
- I know full well...
- I know. Hey, kids!

04:55.576 --> 04:56.943
You excited about your trip?

04:56.944 --> 04:58.211
- Yeah.
- Do you need anything?

04:58.212 --> 05:01.047
- I'm good, thanks.
- Uh... snacks, juice.

05:01.048 --> 05:02.415
How about a bedtime story?

05:02.416 --> 05:04.417
- Uh, have a great trip.
- Thanks.

05:04.418 --> 05:06.119
- Yeah.
- BLAKE: I'll apologize later.

05:06.120 --> 05:07.111
Okay.

05:07.112 --> 05:09.189
Look, 16 of the 17 of the
hottest years on record

05:09.190 --> 05:10.690
have occurred since 2000.

05:10.691 --> 05:13.493
The North Pole is the hottest
it's been in 1,500 years.

05:13.494 --> 05:15.495
Did you see the video
of that starving polar bear?

05:15.496 --> 05:17.097
- Because it is just awful.
- No. I did, I did,

05:17.098 --> 05:18.264
because you showed it
to me several times.

05:18.265 --> 05:19.532
- Okay.
- Let's just go right into my...

05:19.533 --> 05:20.834
Well, look, natural gas
is better than coal...

05:20.835 --> 05:22.669
I will give you that...
but that's still a lot of CO2.

05:22.670 --> 05:24.170
And-and renewables are great,

05:24.171 --> 05:26.406
but you need, like,
12 billion solar roofs

05:26.407 --> 05:28.141
just to match the projected growth

05:28.142 --> 05:30.410
in energy consumption by 2050,

05:30.411 --> 05:32.946
which wind and solar won't
even come close to filling,

05:32.947 --> 05:34.881
unless something magical happens,

05:34.882 --> 05:37.584
which doesn't seem like
a very good plan to me.

05:37.585 --> 05:39.085
You are preaching to the choir, man.

05:39.086 --> 05:41.221
Do you know how many
Americans have died

05:41.222 --> 05:43.857
from commercial nuclear power
accidents since World War II?

05:43.858 --> 05:45.692
- Zero.
- Zero.

05:45.693 --> 05:47.694
And that includes Three Mile Island.

05:47.695 --> 05:49.329
People only died at Chernobyl

05:49.330 --> 05:51.164
because they didn't have
a containment dome.

05:51.165 --> 05:52.399
And when it comes to waste,

05:52.400 --> 05:55.235
the world's entire
supply of spent uranium

05:55.236 --> 05:57.670
from reactors could fit
on a single football field.

05:57.671 --> 05:59.973
Meanwhile, this expo has the potential

05:59.974 --> 06:01.574
to generate thousands of green jobs.

06:01.575 --> 06:04.778
I know. I guess it's
picking our battles.

06:04.779 --> 06:07.347
Besides, we can't even begin
to turn the tide on nuclear

06:07.348 --> 06:09.983
until we have backing from
a major environmental group,

06:09.984 --> 06:14.387
like the... I don't know...
NRDC or Climate Defense Force.

06:14.388 --> 06:16.556
- (SIGHS)
- Yeah.

06:16.557 --> 06:19.225
All right.

06:19.226 --> 06:21.761
I'll give the heads-up to
the ECA and the Expo Unit

06:21.762 --> 06:23.830
about the redesign.

06:23.831 --> 06:25.865
- All right. Hey, Blake?
- Yeah.

06:25.866 --> 06:27.901
You've done really good work.

06:27.902 --> 06:29.869
Thank you.

06:29.870 --> 06:32.171
Yeah.

06:34.874 --> 06:37.877
The British ship <i>Laconia</i>
was carrying more

06:37.878 --> 06:40.280
than 2,000 soldiers,
crew and passengers

06:40.281 --> 06:43.083
when it was torpedoed and sunk
by a German U-boat.

06:43.084 --> 06:45.985
And the German crewmen
were actually in the process

06:45.986 --> 06:49.522
of rescuing the survivors
when they were spotted

06:49.523 --> 06:54.594
by USAAF bomber pilot
Lieutenant James D. Harden.

06:54.595 --> 06:56.296
Even though the Germans

06:56.297 --> 06:58.364
broadcast their humanitarian intent

06:58.365 --> 07:01.334
on open channels and were flying
the-the Red Cross flag,

07:01.335 --> 07:02.669
what did Harden do?

07:02.670 --> 07:04.704
- He bombed the sub.
- That's right.

07:04.705 --> 07:07.907
The panicked U-boat crew threw
the survivors off the deck

07:07.908 --> 07:09.542
to make their escape.

07:09.543 --> 07:12.946
More than a thousand people
died, including civilians.

07:12.947 --> 07:15.048
It was hushed up at the time,
and Harden even

07:15.049 --> 07:17.750
won a medal, but in today's world,

07:17.751 --> 07:20.286
would his actions classify
as a war crime?

07:20.287 --> 07:21.955
Yeah.

07:21.956 --> 07:25.258
Yes. There were clearly
innocents aboard the sub.

07:25.259 --> 07:27.127
Harden and his senior officer

07:27.128 --> 07:28.962
who issued the order
should have been prosecuted.

07:28.963 --> 07:30.630
MAN: Prosecuted?

07:30.631 --> 07:33.166
For not taking the word
of an enemy U-boat commander?

07:33.167 --> 07:35.335
The sub had just sunk
an Allied vessel.

07:35.336 --> 07:37.403
Harden knew if he didn't
destroy the sub now,

07:37.404 --> 07:39.606
it would just go on
to sink more ships,

07:39.607 --> 07:41.541
cost more lives.

07:41.542 --> 07:42.909
As a fellow fighter pilot,

07:42.910 --> 07:44.410
I sure know what I would have done.

07:44.411 --> 07:48.114
Thomas Aquinas said that war is just

07:48.115 --> 07:49.682
if the ultimate goal is peace.

07:49.683 --> 07:51.851
Harden was acting
for the greater good.

07:51.852 --> 07:53.620
Well argued, Lieutenant Hill,

07:53.621 --> 07:55.455
but with all due respect to Aquinas,

07:55.456 --> 07:57.023
there were 80 women and children

07:57.024 --> 07:59.292
in the lifeboats that Harden bombed.

07:59.293 --> 08:02.160
Was killing them
in support of the greater good?

08:03.363 --> 08:05.865
Just something to consider.

08:05.866 --> 08:08.101
All right, that's it for today.
That was a very good discussion.

08:08.102 --> 08:10.136
Thanks. Oh, and papers, please...

08:10.137 --> 08:13.206
Stoic strength and
Epictetus' teleology.

08:13.207 --> 08:15.507
Hard copies and PDFs, okay?

08:16.643 --> 08:19.179
Uh, is it okay if I drop off my paper

08:19.180 --> 08:20.847
- later, Dr. McCord?
- Yeah. Is everything okay?

08:20.848 --> 08:23.183
Yeah, I just want to read
over it one more time.

08:23.184 --> 08:24.150
Okay, just make sure I get it

08:24.151 --> 08:25.351
before my last class ends at 6:00.

08:25.352 --> 08:28.520
Uh, nice Aquinas reference,
by the way.

08:30.190 --> 08:32.157
(PROTESTERS CLAMORING)

08:34.193 --> 08:35.528
These governments scramble

08:35.529 --> 08:38.063
for the last drops of oil,
and who suffers?

08:38.065 --> 08:40.732
The untold millions
in the developing world,

08:40.734 --> 08:42.202
who are the least responsible

08:42.203 --> 08:44.003
for this global warming catastrophe.

08:44.004 --> 08:46.439
- That's right.
- We call on the Arctic Council

08:46.440 --> 08:48.841
to enact a permanent ban
on all drilling

08:48.842 --> 08:50.677
in the North Pole region!

08:50.678 --> 08:52.078
- (CHEERING)
- ELIZABETH: <i>We've always</i>

08:52.079 --> 08:55.281
<i>insisted that
the Northwest Passage was in</i>

08:55.282 --> 08:56.849
- international waters.
- With good reason.

08:56.850 --> 08:58.117
JASON: An ice-free passage

08:58.118 --> 08:59.719
could shorten shipping routes
between Asia

08:59.720 --> 09:02.355
and the Eastern U.S.
by up to 5,000 miles.

09:02.356 --> 09:03.523
(PROTESTERS SHOUTING)

09:03.524 --> 09:04.924
Piper let me

09:04.925 --> 09:06.326
read the notes for her article.

09:06.327 --> 09:07.594
You see that?

09:07.595 --> 09:09.596
Even high schoolers get it.

09:09.597 --> 09:14.033
But now Canada's flexing with
the stupid HMS... whatever.

09:14.034 --> 09:15.635
<i>- Wanderer.</i>
- Wanderer.

09:15.636 --> 09:19.405
Right. They ought to wander
over to the Pentagon

09:19.406 --> 09:22.175
where they'd see that our
force projection in the Arctic

09:22.176 --> 09:23.710
is lame.

09:23.711 --> 09:26.246
How many icebreakers does
the Coast Guard have again?

09:26.247 --> 09:28.314
- Two.
- And one of them's in dry dock.

09:28.315 --> 09:29.749
JASON: That's what you get for

09:29.750 --> 09:31.317
failing to invest
in the end of the world.

09:31.318 --> 09:32.793
Don't you need to go
downstairs somewhere?

09:32.794 --> 09:34.387
- Yeah...
- (KNOCKING)

09:34.388 --> 09:38.024
The point is, we need
to project a united front

09:38.025 --> 09:40.360
to keep Russia at bay, and I think

09:40.361 --> 09:41.995
- we should Le...
- Hey, let's do it.

09:41.996 --> 09:43.496
- Hey, Piper.
- Hi.

09:43.497 --> 09:44.731
Are you ready

09:44.732 --> 09:46.099
for your big interview?

09:46.100 --> 09:48.801
Absolutely. Thanks again for the
opportunity, Madam Elizabeth.

09:48.802 --> 09:51.170
- (LAUGHS)
- I mean... Elizabeth.

09:51.171 --> 09:53.806
Sorry. I know you want me
to call you by your first name.

09:53.807 --> 09:55.608
No. Actually, Madam Elizabeth...

09:55.609 --> 09:56.643
I think that's kind of badass.

09:56.644 --> 09:57.710
- I like it.
- JASON: Okay, we're... let's...

09:57.711 --> 09:59.178
Okay, we're gonna...

09:59.179 --> 10:01.581
And thank you for the hotel room.

10:01.582 --> 10:03.683
Of course.
You guys have fun, all right?

10:03.684 --> 10:05.652
- Don't get arrested.
- JAY: Oh, heads up.

10:05.653 --> 10:08.087
Word among the staff is that
Minister Chen is on the prowl.

10:08.088 --> 10:09.255
Flew in last night.

10:09.256 --> 10:10.623
Of course he did.

10:10.624 --> 10:12.425
CHEN: <i>Secretary McCord.</i>

10:12.426 --> 10:14.661
Another auspicious crossing of paths.

10:14.662 --> 10:17.864
Minister Chen, it is
lovely to see you again.

10:17.865 --> 10:19.365
(LAUGHING): Yes, I'm sure.

10:19.366 --> 10:21.901
But you must know that China
has recently declared itself

10:21.902 --> 10:24.404
- a near-Arctic power.
- I don't even know what that means.

10:24.405 --> 10:27.607
Probably has something to do
with all the nuclear-powered

10:27.608 --> 10:29.942
icebreaker ships
they've been secretly building.

10:29.943 --> 10:32.545
If you are referring
to our research vessels,

10:32.546 --> 10:35.415
they make vital contributions
to the study of marine life,

10:35.416 --> 10:38.518
including the language
of killer whales.

10:38.519 --> 10:41.454
Okay. It's nice to see you.

10:41.455 --> 10:43.923
We are no longer content with mere

10:43.924 --> 10:45.491
observer status.

10:45.492 --> 10:48.628
Our access to the Arctic is
vital to the global economy.

10:48.629 --> 10:50.897
The designation
"Arctic power" is based

10:50.898 --> 10:52.365
on simple geography, Minister.

10:52.366 --> 10:54.100
Due respect, but
"near" doesn't cut it.

10:54.101 --> 10:57.337
Unless you want
to include Poland, Mongolia.

10:57.338 --> 10:58.938
- Kazakhstan, Netherlands.
- Yeah.

10:58.939 --> 11:00.907
This isn't a question of latitude.

11:00.908 --> 11:03.009
ELIZABETH: Actually, it is.

11:03.010 --> 11:05.645
The latitude that borders the Arctic.

11:05.646 --> 11:08.348
If you'll excuse me.

11:08.349 --> 11:12.618
NISSEN: <i>We all appreciate the
urgency of climate change.</i>

11:12.619 --> 11:14.954
Progress cannot be made

11:14.955 --> 11:17.657
until Canada drops
their aggressive new claim

11:17.658 --> 11:19.125
on the Northwest Passage.

11:19.126 --> 11:20.526
WARREN: Our claim goes back

11:20.527 --> 11:21.794
to the HMS <i>Wanderer.</i>

11:21.795 --> 11:24.564
Please. Enough
with your magical sailing ship.

11:24.565 --> 11:25.544
Which sank in 1848.

11:25.545 --> 11:27.934
KONSTANTIN: When Canada
was a part of Britain.

11:27.935 --> 11:29.302
I'll remind you that Canada
has the world's

11:29.303 --> 11:30.370
longest Arctic coastline.

11:30.371 --> 11:32.238
KONSTANTIN: 60%

11:32.239 --> 11:35.041
of all Arctic land area is in Russia,

11:35.042 --> 11:38.644
along with 80%
of the Arctic's population.

11:38.645 --> 11:41.948
But Greenland's continental
shelf extends to the North Pole.

11:41.949 --> 11:43.916
According to whom? You?

11:43.917 --> 11:45.151
ELIZABETH: While we're at it,

11:45.152 --> 11:48.221
America has its own claims
on the Chukchi Ridge.

11:48.222 --> 11:50.022
Which is Russian.

11:50.023 --> 11:51.858
We recognize the ambiguity.

11:51.859 --> 11:55.027
Which is why we propose
an independent survey

11:55.028 --> 11:56.596
of the Arctic seabed,

11:56.597 --> 11:58.364
administered by the U.N.

11:58.365 --> 12:02.234
and funded by the members
of this council.

12:03.703 --> 12:06.806
The domestic reaction

12:06.807 --> 12:08.975
to such an agreement
could be complicated.

12:08.976 --> 12:13.111
Which is why I suggest we keep
the terms classified. For now.

12:14.580 --> 12:16.482
We Norwegians would consider
such a proposal.

12:16.483 --> 12:18.618
In principle, Denmark agrees.

12:18.619 --> 12:20.653
Russia has no objection.

12:20.654 --> 12:23.222
Provided that Canada withdraws

12:23.223 --> 12:25.358
its latest far-fetched claim.

12:25.359 --> 12:28.795
A sunken ship. Preposterous.

12:28.796 --> 12:31.097
It's hard to argue
with a neutral survey.

12:31.098 --> 12:32.832
The people of Canada are willing

12:32.833 --> 12:35.568
to provisionally withdraw
our perfectly reasonable

12:35.569 --> 12:38.805
and genuine claim based on the
sinking of the HMS <i>Wanderer.</i>

12:38.806 --> 12:41.073
In that case, I'd like
to propose a short recess

12:41.074 --> 12:42.875
so we can read the American proposal.

12:42.876 --> 12:45.912
- Seconded.
- KLEVAN: Adjourned.

12:45.913 --> 12:48.414
Hey. Just under the wire.

12:48.415 --> 12:50.516
Yeah. My mom says my
head's in the clouds.

12:50.517 --> 12:52.051
She has no idea.

12:52.052 --> 12:54.487
Thinking about flying even when
you're on the ground, huh?

12:54.488 --> 12:56.222
Yeah. I remember.

12:56.223 --> 12:57.857
Was it hard to give it up?

12:57.858 --> 13:01.394
(SIGHS) Pulling six Gs
in a Split S? Brutal.

13:01.395 --> 13:03.863
But lucky for me, there were
other things I wanted to do.

13:03.864 --> 13:06.933
Spend more time with my family,
write, teach.

13:06.934 --> 13:09.469
But, uh, the freedom, the rush...

13:09.470 --> 13:10.937
oh, man, I still dream about it.

13:10.938 --> 13:13.773
First time I went up,

13:13.774 --> 13:16.342
my dad snuck me into a Lockheed Vega

13:16.343 --> 13:18.344
at a county air show.

13:18.345 --> 13:20.613
It was my fifth birthday.

13:20.614 --> 13:22.381
I guess he was hoping I'd like it.

13:22.382 --> 13:24.849
Join the family business, you know.

13:26.419 --> 13:28.254
But when I saw the earth fall away

13:28.255 --> 13:32.325
and disappear beneath the clouds,

13:32.326 --> 13:34.727
I knew I was never gonna feel
at home on the ground again.

13:34.728 --> 13:37.697
I'm sure he'd be very proud.
I know your mom is.

13:37.698 --> 13:40.433
Thanks, Dr. McCord.

13:40.434 --> 13:42.001
Lieutenant Hill.

13:42.002 --> 13:44.069
Paper.

13:45.371 --> 13:47.072
Thank you.

13:48.674 --> 13:50.443
JAY: <i>Initial responses</i>

13:50.444 --> 13:52.445
seem promising, even
with the fine print.

13:52.446 --> 13:54.213
Good. As soon as we can

13:54.214 --> 13:56.249
resolve the territorial claims,

13:56.250 --> 13:58.717
we can pivot to climate change.

14:00.586 --> 14:02.889
- Cover Bluebird!
- Wait...

14:02.890 --> 14:03.923
- Jason!
- Ma'am, ma'am.

14:03.924 --> 14:05.291
No, Jason!

14:05.292 --> 14:06.592
- Ma'am!
- Jason and Piper.

14:06.593 --> 14:07.760
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

14:07.761 --> 14:09.028
- Jason. Wait, Jason's out there.
- Ma'am.

14:09.029 --> 14:10.963
- The conference is under attack.
- Wait.

14:10.964 --> 14:18.540
Subtitle sync and corrections by
<font color="#FF0000"><b>awaqeded</b></font> for <font color="#FF0000"><b>www.addic7ed.com.</b></font>

14:23.493 --> 14:24.628
(ALARM BLARES)

14:24.629 --> 14:26.763
ELIZABETH: Come on. Come on.

14:26.764 --> 14:28.131
- Come on, Jason.
- Bluebird is secure.

14:28.132 --> 14:29.733
Repeat. Bluebird's secure.

14:29.734 --> 14:31.635
- DS AGENT 2: Evac team inbound.
- It's just going straight to voice mail.

14:31.636 --> 14:33.536
- What about Piper?
- Nothing. How about your tracking app?

14:33.537 --> 14:35.939
No. It's just
"Locating phone." It's...

14:35.940 --> 14:37.440
The network must be overwhelmed.

14:37.441 --> 14:39.276
RCM reports lacerations and burns.

14:39.277 --> 14:40.510
No word on fatalities.

14:40.511 --> 14:42.445
That's it. We are finding Jason.

14:42.446 --> 14:43.913
The Mounties and local PD
are looking for him, ma'am.

14:43.914 --> 14:45.048
- That's bull...
- There's nothing more we can do.

14:45.049 --> 14:46.283
I got a hit! I got Jason.

14:46.284 --> 14:48.417
- Jason's in the hotel.
- (ALARM BLARES)

14:49.552 --> 14:50.887
- He's in the hotel.
- Backup, backup.

14:50.888 --> 14:54.090
Jason?! Jason!

14:54.091 --> 14:55.859
DS AGENT 1: Jason.
- DS AGENT 2: Jason McCord!

14:55.860 --> 14:58.495
Somebody check the shops
and the restaurants downstairs.

14:58.496 --> 15:01.031
- I lost the signal. I lost it.
- Can we get a 20 on Jason?

15:01.032 --> 15:02.495
I want to check Piper's room.
Is he in there?

15:02.496 --> 15:03.373
Ma'am. Ma-Ma'am.

15:03.374 --> 15:04.567
I'm going to have to
insist that you stay...

15:04.568 --> 15:06.336
Yeah, insist while we walk.

15:06.337 --> 15:09.039
- (GROANS)
- Ma'am.

15:09.040 --> 15:10.674
Ma'am, I'm sure he's
gonna be all right.

15:10.675 --> 15:13.209
Piper! Jason.

15:13.210 --> 15:14.577
Honey, are you guys in there?

15:14.578 --> 15:17.781
Pipe... Jason!

15:17.782 --> 15:19.749
(GASPS) Oh. When did you get back?

15:19.750 --> 15:21.284
Hi. What-what are you...? Who-who...?

15:21.285 --> 15:23.153
- Where's Piper? Did she get back?
- Yeah. No. She's fi...

15:23.154 --> 15:24.154
- I-I don't... You don't...
- Okay.

15:24.155 --> 15:25.155
You don't have to...

15:25.156 --> 15:27.123
She's okay. She...

15:27.124 --> 15:29.025
Is that Luther Vandross?

15:29.026 --> 15:30.527
("IF ONLY FOR ONE NIGHT" PLAYING)

15:30.528 --> 15:33.596
♪ To ease away your fear... ♪

15:33.597 --> 15:35.498
Ooh.

15:35.499 --> 15:37.067
♪ It would be so nice... ♪

15:37.068 --> 15:38.868
Oh, God.

15:38.869 --> 15:41.271
♪ If only for one night... ♪

15:41.272 --> 15:43.239
Got it.

15:43.240 --> 15:45.041
Understood.

15:45.042 --> 15:47.077
Ma'am.

15:47.078 --> 15:48.912
Summit's been postponed indefinitely.

15:48.913 --> 15:50.880
Looks like a small group
of masked protesters

15:50.881 --> 15:52.282
from CDF started the riot

15:52.283 --> 15:55.151
by breaking down the barriers
and setting off this IED.

15:55.152 --> 15:56.686
They arrested Bella Rossi

15:56.687 --> 15:58.421
for facilitating a terrorist activity.

15:58.422 --> 16:02.392
All right. Um, I want
you to stay here.

16:02.393 --> 16:04.327
Liaise with Consular Affairs,
talk to Rossi.

16:04.328 --> 16:06.396
If she'll cooperate fully

16:06.397 --> 16:09.532
with the local authorities,
then we'll do whatever we can

16:09.533 --> 16:11.201
to keep her out of Canadian prison.

16:11.202 --> 16:12.702
I mean, assuming she wasn't complicit.

16:12.703 --> 16:14.571
JASON: I'd rather be in prison.

16:14.572 --> 16:15.672
I'm sorry. Did you say something?

16:15.673 --> 16:17.407
I said I'd rather be in prison.

16:17.408 --> 16:19.809
PIPER: Jason, stop.

16:19.810 --> 16:21.376
(SIREN WAILING)

16:27.684 --> 16:30.352
(DOOR OPENS)

16:31.187 --> 16:33.623
Thank you, Frank.

16:33.624 --> 16:35.324
Hey.

16:39.095 --> 16:41.064
Hey.

16:41.065 --> 16:44.501
You just gonna ground me,
get it over with?

16:44.502 --> 16:46.302
You're not getting off that easy.

16:46.303 --> 16:47.537
Okay. Firing squad?

16:47.538 --> 16:48.838
Yeah, that's warmer.

16:48.839 --> 16:50.140
Go upstairs.

16:50.141 --> 16:51.941
We'll have "the talk" tomorrow.

16:51.942 --> 16:53.243
You might want to consider getting rid

16:53.244 --> 16:55.578
of the wise-ass routine.

16:55.579 --> 16:58.081
(SIGHS)

16:58.082 --> 16:59.516
Glass of wine?

16:59.517 --> 17:01.751
No. Scotch.

17:01.752 --> 17:03.586
Hmm.

17:03.587 --> 17:05.521
(SIGHS)

17:05.522 --> 17:09.893
So I talked to Regina
when we dropped off Piper.

17:09.894 --> 17:11.861
Piper takes full responsibility

17:11.862 --> 17:14.497
for the deception.

17:14.498 --> 17:17.066
Says that she just
wanted their first time

17:17.067 --> 17:20.336
to be special and
romantic, and I guess

17:20.337 --> 17:22.539
Jason went along with the plan,

17:22.540 --> 17:24.540
right down to Luther Vandross

17:24.541 --> 17:26.742
and chocolate-covered strawberries.

17:26.743 --> 17:28.645
It's like they wanted
to have sex in the '80s.

17:28.646 --> 17:30.380
(EXHALES)

17:30.381 --> 17:34.584
But Piper's apology does not
get Jason off the hook.

17:34.585 --> 17:37.387
- Oh, not by a long shot.
- Okay.

17:37.388 --> 17:39.088
(SIGHS)

17:39.089 --> 17:40.890
He's the son
of the secretary of state.

17:40.891 --> 17:44.860
We were on an official
U.S. diplomatic mission.

17:45.862 --> 17:47.430
What happened to taking responsibility

17:47.431 --> 17:48.498
for your decisions?

17:48.499 --> 17:49.632
To thinking before you act?

17:49.633 --> 17:52.502
Here I was, thinking that my son,

17:52.503 --> 17:55.004
or at least his... girlfriend,

17:55.005 --> 17:58.641
would be interested
in what I was doing.

17:58.642 --> 18:00.977
Turns out it was all a
ruse just to have sex

18:00.978 --> 18:02.645
in a country that speaks French.

18:02.646 --> 18:04.814
And what, are we supposed
to just continue

18:04.815 --> 18:06.883
to clean up their messes
for the rest of their lives

18:06.884 --> 18:09.586
because they turned out
to be lazy and entitled

18:09.587 --> 18:10.887
and self-destructive?

18:10.888 --> 18:12.455
Willing to risk everything
that's important

18:12.456 --> 18:14.057
in their lives, while we just

18:14.058 --> 18:15.959
whistle past their...

18:15.960 --> 18:18.495
deception and misconduct?

18:18.496 --> 18:20.797
Are we still talking
about Jason and Piper?

18:20.798 --> 18:23.166
(SIGHS) I'm sorry.

18:23.167 --> 18:27.370
I-I-I also had a crappy
situation with a student.

18:27.371 --> 18:28.938
And it's more than a little fraught.

18:28.939 --> 18:31.908
You mean that someone
else's kid screwed up?

18:31.909 --> 18:33.810
I'm all ears. Let's hear it.

18:33.811 --> 18:35.979
He turned in a paper,

18:35.980 --> 18:38.581
and sections of it were
lifted from an essay

18:38.582 --> 18:40.383
by a student of mine from Georgetown.

18:40.384 --> 18:41.885
I guess he found it on the Internet

18:41.886 --> 18:44.287
and didn't realize
it was from my class.

18:44.288 --> 18:46.189
- Wow.
- Yeah.

18:46.190 --> 18:47.924
Has he ever done anything
like this before?

18:47.925 --> 18:49.058
No. That's the thing.

18:49.059 --> 18:50.560
The kid is a rock star.
First in his class

18:50.561 --> 18:52.562
at Air Force Academy,
first in officer's training.

18:52.563 --> 18:55.999
He's a natural pilot and he loves it.

18:56.000 --> 18:59.669
And now I'm gonna have to
report him to the commandant.

18:59.670 --> 19:01.604
Punishment starts with NJP

19:01.605 --> 19:03.473
and could lead to a court-martial.

19:03.474 --> 19:04.707
And, babe...

19:04.708 --> 19:08.177
It's Ellen Hill's son, Andrew.

19:08.178 --> 19:11.147
Oh, my God.

19:11.148 --> 19:14.350
Anything less than him
rising to general

19:14.351 --> 19:16.719
or even president will be

19:16.720 --> 19:19.022
- a bitter disappointment to Ellen.
- I've got to report him.

19:19.023 --> 19:21.090
Things are gonna be a little
awkward at the next NSC meeting.

19:21.091 --> 19:22.724
- (PHONE BUZZING)
- (SCOFFS)

19:23.993 --> 19:25.828
Jay, tell me you have some good news.

19:25.829 --> 19:27.230
JAY: Bella Rossi

19:27.231 --> 19:28.965
turned over the names
of the violent protesters

19:28.966 --> 19:30.199
to Canadian authorities.

19:30.200 --> 19:31.434
Great. Are they in custody?

19:31.435 --> 19:33.970
No, ma'am. The names were all aliases.

19:33.971 --> 19:35.371
Canadian Intelligence traced one

19:35.372 --> 19:38.775
to a Twitter handle controlled
by an Internet research agency

19:38.776 --> 19:41.611
in the Olgino district
of St. Petersburg.

19:41.612 --> 19:43.780
You have to be kidding me.

19:43.781 --> 19:44.948
They're Russian agents, ma'am.

19:44.949 --> 19:47.917
Russia spiked the summit?

19:47.918 --> 19:50.219
Using GRU assets planted inside

19:50.220 --> 19:52.655
an American NGO for more than a year.

19:52.656 --> 19:54.324
That's some deep game.

19:54.325 --> 19:56.960
That's Russia.

19:56.961 --> 20:01.129
Whatever they're up to in the
Arctic, it's just the beginning.

